<br>
-State the reason(s) why you like the program(s) listed above:<br>
Well, Simpsons for humor, obviously. It's declined over the years, but it still makes me laugh. And, though I didn't think I'd like it at first, Batman Beyond is a really intesting concept. The characters and situations are interesting and it's more serious than most US cartoons out there. Gargoyles, though it's been cancelled for several years, is still one of my favorite animated series of all time. Another series that was more serious than other US animation. The storyline was continual and evolving, something lacking not only in US animation, but in animation in general. Characters and relationships changed over time, it didn't remain stagnant. And, though I'm well aware that most people disagree, but that's one of the strong points of the Dragonball (yes, including Z) in my opinion. While you may not care for the subject, I found the characters interesting and they all changed dramatically by series end. I also liked how the story was continuous, in a way not done in any other animation I'm familiar with (or at least not many). Eh, I kind of just threw Gundam on there. I do watch it every week, but I mainly chose it because I liked how deep and involved the storyline was. The thing I liked about all the series were that all the characters were extremely interesting and unique (Gundam excluded; not that they were bad). They're all very developed and you feel like you know them almost.<br>
<br>
-What kind of animated program would you like to see MORE often?<br>
Serious, character focused, with a storyline that doesn't forget what happened last episode. A few more series aimed at a mature audience (like Spawn or something similar) would be nice, but as long as an animated show isn't dumbed down, it can still be enjoyable.<br>
<br>
-What kind of animated program would you like to see LESS of?<br>
Silly, slapsticky, Nickelodeon/Disneyesque toons. Yeah, I liked them as a kid, but they're just aggrivating now. Then there's the extremely cliched and idiotic Japanese animated series. I can't stand Pilot Candidate, for example. Every single character looks almost exactly the same, and they even threw in a catgirl to be even more annoying. Not to mention, what the hell does a catgirl have to do with anything else in that series.<br>
<br>
-What should producers concentrate on more... Style or Content?<br>
Content definitely. Style is great, and hopefully they concentrate on that too, but without any substance, there's not much point.<br>
<br>
-Would you watch an animates series if it was drawn very well but the story is lacking?<br>
Depends. It'd have to be damn good looking, and I don't know if I could watch it even then if the story was terrible. If the story is alright, and the animation/style great, then I might watch it every now and then at least.<br>
<br>
-Would you watch a program if it were poorly animated?<br>
Yes. That's almost a given with certain US animated series. They get so many different animation companies doing different episodes that animation quality can fluctuate wildly. For example, Gargoyles had some butt ugly episodes, but still, some of those are my favorites because the stories in those particular episodes were important or otherwise interesting.<br>
<br>
-With the advent of 3D animated shows coming around, would you prefer to watch those types of shows<br>
than traditional 2D animated shows? <br>
